Hi, I would be glad to work on the REST API cause we will need it soon at work :)
@mistercrunch I've checked a little and it does seem that the automagic with argparse doesn't exist, have you found something on this ?
How would you design it if you were to write it on your own ? I'll see if I can get some time to do it.

You folks raise some interesting points.
@hyperborea is right that there is some value in being able to have a query return a value for use in other tasks.  That could probably be done now with PythonOperator/HiveCliHook.run_cli and EmailOperator.
@r39132 is right that in returning a full query result will often be impractical/impossible from a performance perspective.  The xcom system is designed for return values, not datasets
@bolkedebruin brings up the interesting idea of returning result handles much like Luigi does it.  It would probably make the Airflow batch system more flexible to orient jobs around arbitrary resource handles instead of only execution dates like it is now.  Some issues with this proposal:
- The creation of a resource handle would have to be implemented one-by-one for each operator.  For HiveOperator it might be tricky to identify the precise output if the supplied HQL consists of multiple queries.  Same for Pig scripts with multiple outputs.  For a PythonOperator we'd need a new convention for DAG authors to specify the output handles.
- This output handle approach wouldn't do much for @hyperborea 's original use case. A simple "select count(*)" Hive query would probably return a handle to a temporary directory on HDFS

It seems to me we need two approaches:
1. Create a new operator which executes a single-value Hive query and returns the value via xcom.  The operator raises an exception if the query returned multiple values.
2. Existing operators should, where practical, be modified to return some sort of handle or handles to their output.  In the case of HiveOperator this might mean parsing the log for messages about updated tables or partitions.  Because some operators may update multiple destinations the returned handle may be a nested array.

@thibault-ketterer  It won't. The goals are different.  

`Only_run_latest` will be used for a job like a `daily db snapshot` job. Typically, this type of job needs to run once a day. If it doesn't run for 3 days because the DAG was paused, when the DAG is unpaused, the job should not run 3 times. It should only run for the latest time interval. 

What I propose above is to mark entries manually as "skipped or do not run" so that the scheduler or backfill job does not attempt them. This could be because we know there is a data problem in the time range.
